   - **Crow:** [https://github.com/crowcpp/crow](https://github.com/crowcpp/crow) (Web framework with built-in markdown support)

2. **Structured Parsing:**  Libraries like MarkdownXL provide a structured representation of the markdown document (nodes, elements, etc.). This makes HTML generation more organized and accurate.

3. **Tag Handling:**

   - **Opening and Closing Tags:**  Properly manage opening and closing HTML tags based on markdown elements.  Libraries usually handle this automatically.
   - **Nested Tags:**  Ensure correct nesting of HTML tags when markdown contains nested headings, lists, etc.

4. **Extensions:**  Markdown has various extensions (tables, code blocks, footnotes, etc.). Choose a library that supports the extensions you need.

5. **Example using MarkdownXL (Conceptual):**

   ```cpp
   #include <iostream>
   #include "markdownxl/markdownxl.h" // Include MarkdownXL header

   std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
       markdownxl::Document doc(markdown);
       return doc.toHtml(); // MarkdownXL handles the conversion
   }

   int main() {
       std::string markdown = "# Hello\n## World\n***This is bold***";
       std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
       std::cout << html << std::endl;
       return 0;
   }
   ```

**Key Points:**

- **Don't reinvent the wheel:** Use a proven markdown parsing library for reliability and efficiency.
- **Structured Approach:**  Leverage the structured output provided by libraries for cleaner HTML generation.
- **Extension Support:** Select a library that aligns with your required markdown features.



